projection_comment: Monster season with 22.8 touches/game and 40% of his runs gained 5 or more yards after just 27% of his runs did so in 2016.
Dallas OL only 20th in Yds before contact, but should improve and in addition to 38% available target share, there's a massive rushing role and limited work in '17.
Finished as RB1 2x and RB2 1x in the 3 seasons with 12+ games since 2014, but also 400+ touches last two years so mileage is adding up.
Well-rested stud who posted 2000 total yards with 8th-most 407.8 PPR points and 120 targets ever.
May see TD regression, but he was first RB over 300 PPR points with fewer than 150 carries, but should go from 120 to around 150+ with Ingram out 4 weeks.
Very good numbers and before injury in Wk 7, forced at least 1 missed tackle 19.2% of carries, 6th-best, and OG stud Norwell will help, so health only concern.
Passed rookie season w/ flying colors and his 18.5 FPG 15th-best rookie season among RBs all-time, plus a strong 84% catch rate and huge role with Mahomes still raw.
Showed a ton of game at 4.8 YPC and role in pass game increasing, but serious OL issues and Murray will play a lot.
Complete back who should be a slam-dunk due to big plays, receiving, and outstanding character and OC Shurmur was great for McKinnon last year.
Another sub-4.0 YPC season for him in '17 but with well over 20 touches/game and 68% of their carries and 12% of targets, he produces with volume.
His 113 targets the 13th-most in season among RBs since '92 and looking like the clear workhorse so looking good.
Their OL opened up just 1.29 yards before 1st contact, 9th-fewest, yet 2 OL upgrades in '18 and stellar 88% catch rate and already scored nice TD.
Stats down in '17 and averaged only one fewer touch per game in 2017 (16.6) than 2016 (17.6), but overall offense should improve and he's still a baller.
Very good runner, but his 63.4% CR last 2 years worst among RBs with 50 targets and his 63.4% catch rate last 2 worst among RBs with at least 50 targets
Some competition with Gore/Ballage, but Wks 13-17 played on 86% of snaps, 1st in rush yds (444) and in yards after contact (4.1), and 8th in PPR Points (88.4).
Might be overrated runner, but Shanahan's scheme will help him, yet he's already banged up so availability is still a big question.
8 straight years with 1000+ yards scrimmage but now 2500+ touches and Bill OL and offense looks prohibitive, plus legal situation is worrisome.
Impressive 4.9 YPC and a shockingly-good 91% catch rate means he's good enough to handle half the workload here with Henry.
Solid 80% catch rate but less effective and only 3.7 YPC but slimmer this summer and Foreman no lock for Week 1 as 8/1.
Can dominate the stat sheet with volume but can also post 28/51 rushing like Week 16, and a healthy Lewis will keep Henry's volume and reliability down.
Impressively handled 17+ touches 7 straight games to end 2017 and favorite to carry rushing load, and it helps that Dixon already banged up in camp.
Tremendous with 4.9 YPC and 82% catch rate but out 4 games and his 12 TDs equaled his 2015-2016 output.
Great 83% CR and fantastic 1.3 points per touch, and will get more than '17's 10 touches a game if healthy, but lingering knee injury means some downside.
Only 10 carries a game in Philly, but a great 5.8 YPC and should get 13-15 carries a week plus 1-2 catches.
A reach in 1st and a shaky OL, while Carson and others could keep production down early with Penny injured and having gained some weight.
Finished as a top-15 scoring RB just 3X in 2017 as receiving and TD numbers predictably dropped, but still a solid option with big upside if Freeman is out.
Nothing particularly exceptional about his game and no lock to be the guy, yet a huge role there for taking, so could pan out with volume behind improved OL.
A solid 4.3 YPC on 13.8 carries a game and 67% of their RZ carries and good OL, and big run in preseason opener shows he still has juice.
Strong 4.3 YPC and 74.6% catch rate as a rookie and he was under-utilized, yet new staff is equipped to unleash him.
Only 3.6 YPC but solid 73% catch rate and handled 24% of their touches and produced with volume, and Jones suspension helps.
Durability issues remain and not 100% yet in Aug, but averaged 5 targets/game but outstanding 13.08 YPR and 1.28 FP per touch and Guice injury is huge.
Career YPC avg. of 4.2 and 70% catch rate look good on this roster, so good bet to collect 200+ touches, yet we were told 8/10 Powell will be very involved.
Borderline special, receiving game can grow, and 40% of NE '17 RB opportunities avail but ball-security issues and knee is a real problem in Aug.
He'll open season as #2, but only .78 FP per touch in 2017 and he won't match his 16% of SF's reception in Cleveland with Duke there, plus Chubb a better power runner.
A solid runner and not a zero in pass game with 84% catch rate on 19 targets, and could carve out active early-down role in RBBC with rookie Jones struggling.
Excellent season in 2017 but won't get the 36% of Cle rushing TDs and 24% target share in 2018 so numbers will go down.
Only 5.2 carries/game and 84 touches, plus Sproles back in the mix, but they love him and his outstanding 1.08 FP per touch bodes well.
An excellent 1.03 FP per touch last year and a good PPR bench piece, but will likely see decrease in the 165 touches he had if Mixon is healthy.
Excellent 1.35 FP per game in PPR, and looking great this summer, plus Rex and Michel dealing with knee issues can only help.
We don't love him and he has struggled mightily behind Barber in preseason, but he has solid skills and excellent straight-line explosion if he gets his head on straight.
Sea didn't draft Penny due to Carson's injury, yet Carson is giving Penny a real challenge and with Penny injured now Carson should open the year in a significant role.
Crowded backfield and we're not high on his talent so hard to back with Blount and Riddick here, but did look good in opener.
Posted a solid 78.95% catch rate but only 3.6 YPC in 2 years shows his rushing limitations, yet well in the mix in possible RBBC.
Impressive rookie showing as 44% of 80 carries gained 5 or more yds while just 32% of Williamsâ€™ did, but won't catch it much and 2-game suspension really hurts chances.
Crowell added and only 2.2 TGT/game, yet McGuire injury helps and we're told he's going to get 8-12 carries most weeks.
Excellent early-down back who's a better downhill thumper than Hyde and upside selection for depth, but Hyde if healthy won't be easy to unseat.
YPC down from 5.9 to 3.8 with almost exact number of carries and role in limbo but Jones' issues this summer help, as does Williams' ankle issue.
Showed dazzling potential at times but a staggering 32% of carries failed to gain yardage, plus plenty of competition and Reich likely uses multiple backs.
Way up to 5.2 YPC on 58 carries but real value comes in passing game and good bet to get 20 touches/game if LF is out.
Can still get things done but he's now 35 and should take on more of a mentoring role here, so hard to back with Drake and Ballage good options.
Asked to take a pay cut in 2018 because he isn't a good #1 RB, yet a solid backup and handcuff to Cook as he can do it all and looks better in 2018.
Only 3.4 YPC on 5.2 carries/game, yet only 4.4 targets/game so while he has clear PPR value, upside seems limited at this point.
Very capable receiver whose never been below 4.0 YPC and could absorb some of the 198 carries Stewart had in 2017, yet a non-factor in opener.
Keeps chugging along and his 4.4 YPC his best since 2014, yet Det OL has to improve run-blocking and lots of competition for snaps and touches.
A strong 5.5 YPC and 77% catch rate but really only actively involved for 5 weeks so not much more than deep backup and Gordon handcuff.
He's a good bet for 15+ carries most weeks so has some value, but body may break down when he piles up touches.
A solid 4.4 YPC and .82 FP per touch, but not exactly a good complement to McKinnon plus injured 8/9 and will miss time.
Good size, some wiggle, versatility and size unique to this roster, so he landed in a great spot as he's in the convo for early-down or every-down work.
Solid pass-catcher but a pitiful 5.6 YPR and still hasn't rushed for more than 4.0 YPC so just a guy, yet Dixon on roster bubble.
Likely a satellite player, but he runs better than most think and can catch it, so a decent sleeper as Colts will likely utilize 2-3 RBs though he has had major fumbling problems in preseason.
The ageless wonder should still have juice in his 13th season, but his role won't likely see more than 6-8 opportunities a game.
He played well in the second preseason game and looked good, so he's got a chance to carve out a role if he keeps it up.
Very good #2 here and he'll get some work behind McCoy and potentially vulture TDs, plus upside if McCoy is out.
Hoping to regain rookie form following off-season ankle surgery, and he's looked better than Gillislee all summer, so deep sleeper.
Not overly talented but a solid 4.3 YPC and solid work in the passing game, yet Barkley add was the kiss of death.
Solid backup who was at 4.2 YPC and 83% catch rate on 23 targets, so their best handcuff to Zeke, pending Bo Scarbrough's summer showing.
A pathetic 2.9 YPC his last two seasons and next to impossible to pin down value here with Lynch around.
A great 5.5 YPC and 75% catch rate first two seasons, but fewer than 100 touches a year his first two seasons.
Looked good averaging 4.2 YPC on 78 carries and not a zero in the passing game, but has to prove healthy and still not a lock of Week 1 as of 8/1.
Still on the roster in training camp but they added Damien Williams and have Hunt so not much to get excited about.
Decent rookie showing for sure with over 100 opportunities, but only 3.6 YPC and behind Crowell/Powell, and will miss all of training camp with injury.
Not much to get excited about behind so-so OL, but could get 10 or so carries a game and some goal line work.
Miserable 3.3 YPC in 2017 and won't get the 12 carries a game he got last year, but could be traded in final year of rookie deal.
Only 64 touches and 11 out of a possible 32 games played, and a lot of talent and versatility and actually play in preseason!
Played for Shanahan and excels on zone run game, and decent bet for early-down work if he makes the team.
A favorite of HC Koetter but only 73 touches and a mediocre 3.8 YPC, which is his career avg.
Only 32 carries and 0 catches his '17 rookie year but he remains for now their best handcuff for Bell.
A whopping 8.3 YPC on 30 carries shows his juice and he should have a role as a changeup, albeit a small one.
Underrated talent we liked a lot, and if he is the #2 behind Gurley he'll be worth holding as handcuff as he can run it and catch it well.
Inconsistent in college, but big time physical tools and versatility give him a chance to surprise, yet Drake is the man and Gore old reliable.
A nice 75% catch rate on 68 career targets, but down to 2.7 YPC and yet to have 100+ touches in his 2 seasons, and now he's hurt.
Got his chance as a rookie but only 3.4 YPC and a poor .55 FP per touch and AP added is a crusher.
Only 5 games and 7 touches in rookie season and plenty of competition with Booker/Freeman, but he is talented and had a good 2017 camp.
He's been on their roster since 2017 and has a lot of talent, so he could help fill in while Ingram is out.
Welp, with Mack likely out Week 1, Michael may actually be their best lead back, but not worth drafting yet.
He's competing with Kelley but both should lose early-down job to AP so no value now.
On and off the roster in 2017 but he's on roster for 2018 and could have some PPR value if he's here.
He's 29 already and waived by Ari in 2017 and unsigned as of May's end.
In theory he's a good complement to McKinnon and a talented runner, but lost rookie year and Alf Morris add is not a good sign.
Looks like he will make this team as the #3 and could see some snaps as a changeup.
Ultra productive in college, but DJ is the main weapon here and Logan will give him competition.
Panthers told us what they think of him with CJ Anderson signing, so he's only CJA's backup.
He's had a great summer and should make the team and he may even challenge Ivory for touches behind McCoy.
Only 3.6 YPC on 85 career carries and only 14/54 rushing and 4/7 receiving Week 17 filling in for Gurley, so he can be replaced.
Foreman as of late-June still not a lock for Week 1, so Blue needs to be on the radar.
Excellent receiver but he's moreso a potential option in 2019 with Tevin Coleman an impending free agent.
Steady receiver with 74% catch rate in 4 years, but a weak 3.6 career YPC average and no lock to have a role.
UDFA who's put himself in the mix to make the team with Ingram out first 4 games, he has some quickness and versatility.
Interesting changeup option as he's versatile and explosive, but has to earn job after lost rookie 2017 season.
Slipped in the draft and won't have any value unless Zeke is out and even then Rod Smith is at worst 3rd down back.
He may be a better bet to make the team than Hill, but we'll see what the preseason shows, and Michel's health.
He's had 5 good games out of 34 in his career and will be lucky to make this roster.
Out for the season with ACL.
He's retired.
